The symptoms suggest the patient is experiencing Guillain-Barré syndrome, with weakness in the lower extremities, absent deep tendon reflexes, but intact sensation to pinprick and light touch. The elevated protein in the cerebrospinal fluid also supports this diagnosis. Thymoma, urinary incontinence, and hypertrophic cardiomyopathy are not directly related to Guillain-Barré syndrome.
